<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SAN GABRIEL; MOTORCYCLE PATROLS BACK ON THE STREETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After being phased out 22 years ago, motorcycle police returned to San 
Gabriel's city streets this month under a $375,000 grant from the National 
Highway Safety Program. 
</P>
<P>
 The two officers and a sergeant who began cruising city streets are part of an 
overall traffic safety program that includes educational lectures and sobriety 
checkpoints. The grant enabled the city to acquire a radar display trailer that 
flashes the speed of cars to motorists driving past and to obtain hand-held 
laser beam speed detectors to replace the older radar units. 
</P>
<P>
 Also under the grant, San Gabriel officers must increase the number of 
citations given motorists for hazardous driving, such as drunk driving or 
running red lights, Police Capt. Richard Arnold said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
