<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY; RELIGION: HISTORY OF BLACK MORMONISM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Until 1978, the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints barred African 
Americans from the priesthood, although some have been included as members of 
the church since its early days in the 1830s. 
</P>
<P>
 Since the priesthood ban was lifted, blacks have helped fuel the Mormon 
Church's 10% annual growth rate, according to organizers of a Black History 
Month exhibit at the Los Angeles Mormon temple's visitor center at 10777 Santa 
Monica Blvd. in Westwood. It features photographs, artifacts, heirlooms and a 
video about black Mormons in the United States and several African countries. 
</P>
<P>
 The exhibit will be open daily from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. through Feb. 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
