<P>
YEN CHIA-KAN; FORMER TAIWAN PRESIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Yen Chia-kan, 88, president of Taiwan from 1975 to 1978. Born in central 
mainland China, Yen fled the 1949 Communist takeover and helped Chiang Kai-shek 
set up the Nationalist Chinese government in Taiwan.Yen served as President 
Chiang's economic minister, finance minister, premier and vice president. As 
the economic policy-maker in the 1950s and 1960s, Yen was largely credited with 
moving the island from poverty to flourishing global manufacturing center. When 
Chiang died in 1975, Yen was vice president and succeeded him, completing the 
remaining three years in Chiang's term and stepping aside in favor of Chiang's 
son, Chiang Ching-kuo. On Dec. 24 in Taipei of heart failure. 
