<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRISON CONDITIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * John Garamendi's reference to prisons as "concrete palaces" (Dec. 29) as 
well as the statement " . . . when our kids have schools that are as good as 
prisons" deserves much refinement. As a firsthand point of view, I am sure your 
readers would like to know that the prison where I am currently incarcerated is 
a far cry from a concrete palace. 
</P>
<P>
 I am currently sentenced to 16 months for a computer crime, have no violence 
on my record, and in no way expected the conditions here at Folsom. There are 
no gymnasiums, no computers, or any kind of adult education whatsoever. The 
overcrowding makes it impossible to even work. The current wait is a minimum of 
four months. 
</P>
<P>
 Furthermore, the inmates spend most of the time locked up in 5 foot by 12 foot 
cells. Showers are a privilege. The access to the yard is only two to three 
times a week, and most showers are taken outside no matter what the temperature 
is. In essence, this is a human warehouse.  
</P>
<P>
 STUART GOTTLIEB 
</P>
<P>
 Folsom State Prison 
</P>
</TEXT>
