<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMAN WHO SUED ACTOR FOX WINS DAMAGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE TAMAKI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Los Angeles Superior Court jury awarded $104,386 in damages to a woman who 
bought a Studio City home from actor Michael J. Fox and then sued the movie 
star for landscaping and repairs. 
</P>
<P>
 Michele Ader said Wednesday in a telephone interview that the jury ordered Fox 
to pay the damages after finding he breached a contract over the sale of the 
home.The same jury found Fox had not committed fraud or negligent 
misrepresentation. 
</P>
<P>
 Drew Pomerance, an attorney representing Ader, had asked the jury to award his 
client more than $325,000 -- nearly half the $750,000 selling price of the home 
-- to replace 14 cypress trees and other landscaping and to repair a damaged 
pool, a leaky roof and a potential problem with the home's foundation. 
</P>
<P>
 Attorneys for Fox could not be reached for comment after business hours. 
However, one of them, Martin Snyder, told the Associated Press that while he 
disagreed with the verdict, "obviously, the jury felt that some of the repairs 
had not been attended to." 
</P>
<P>
 Snyder said he would consult with Fox to decide whether to ask a judge to 
reduce the award. 
</P>
<P>
 "We disagree with the calculation of amounts," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Ader said that in addition to the $104,386 damage award, the actor will also 
be responsible for her legal fees, which she estimates at $150,000. JULIE 
TAMAKI 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012094-0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 005691 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
